Project Idea

This project classifies a business problem description into the correct machine learning paradigm:

Supervised Learning
Unsupervised Learning
Reinforcement Learning
Example:

Predict customer churn using past data
The system returns:

ML Type: Supervised
Confidence: 90%
Reason: Keyword "predict" detected, and the model agreed.
Suggested Algorithms: Logistic Regression, Decision Tree, Random Forest...
5-Step Workflow: ...
Main files:

ml_paradigm_classifier.py contains the ML logic
data/ml_paradigm_dataset.csv contains the dataset
app.py contains the Streamlit web app
1. Dataset

The dataset is a CSV file with two columns:

text,label
"Predict customer churn using previous purchase and support history",supervised
"Cluster customers into segments based on buying behavior",unsupervised
"Train an agent to choose prices that maximize long term profit",reinforcement
The text column contains a business problem description.

The label column contains the correct ML type:

supervised
unsupervised
reinforcement
I used 45 examples total: 15 for each category. This keeps the project beginner-friendly while still giving the model enough examples to learn basic patterns.

2. What Each ML Type Means

Supervised Learning means the model learns from labeled data.

Example:

Predict customer churn using past data
Here, we already have past examples where customers either churned or did not churn. The model learns from those answers.

Common supervised tasks:

prediction
classification
forecasting
detecting fraud using labeled examples
Algorithms:

Logistic Regression
Decision Tree
Random Forest
Support Vector Machine
Gradient Boosting
Unsupervised Learning means the model works with data that has no target label.

Example:

Group customers based on buying behavior
There is no predefined answer like “customer belongs to group A.” The model tries to discover hidden patterns by itself.

Common unsupervised tasks:

clustering
grouping
segmentation
anomaly detection
dimensionality reduction
Algorithms:

K-Means
Hierarchical Clustering
DBSCAN
PCA
Gaussian Mixture Models
Reinforcement Learning means an agent learns by taking actions and receiving rewards.

Example:

Train an agent to choose prices that maximize long term profit
The system learns through trial and error. Good actions get rewards, bad actions get penalties.

Common reinforcement learning tasks:

game AI
robot navigation
traffic signal control
pricing agents
recommendation agents
Algorithms:

Q-Learning
Deep Q-Networks
Policy Gradient
Actor-Critic
Multi-Armed Bandits
3. Preprocessing

Before training, text must be cleaned.

The function clean_text() does three things:

text = str(text).lower()
text = text.translate(str.maketrans("", "", string.punctuation))
text = " ".join(text.split())
That means:

Converts text to lowercase
"Predict Customer Churn" becomes "predict customer churn"

Removes punctuation
"predict churn!" becomes "predict churn"

Removes extra spaces
"predict churn" becomes "predict churn"

Why this matters: machine learning models treat text literally. Without cleaning, "Predict" and "predict" may be treated differently.

4. Feature Extraction With TF-IDF

Machine learning models cannot directly understand text. They need numbers.

So we use:

TfidfVectorizer(preprocessor=clean_text)
TF-IDF means Term Frequency-Inverse Document Frequency.

Simple meaning:

Words that appear often in one sentence are important.
Words that appear everywhere are less useful.
Useful words get higher numeric values.
Example:

Predict customer churn
TF-IDF converts it into a numeric vector like:

predict: 0.62
customer: 0.41
churn: 0.66
Not exactly like this visually, but conceptually this is what happens.

Why TF-IDF is used: it is simple, fast, and very common for beginner text classification projects.

5. Model: Logistic Regression

The model used is:

LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000, random_state=42)
Even though the name says “regression,” Logistic Regression is commonly used for classification.

Here it performs multi-class classification, meaning it chooses between more than two classes:

supervised
unsupervised
reinforcement
Why Logistic Regression was chosen:

beginner-friendly
fast to train
works well with TF-IDF
gives probability scores using predict_proba()
easy to explain in a presentation
6. Pipeline

The code uses an sklearn Pipeline:

Pipeline(
    steps=[
        ("tfidf", TfidfVectorizer(preprocessor=clean_text)),
        ("classifier", LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000, random_state=RANDOM_STATE)),
    ]
)
A pipeline connects multiple steps together.

The flow is:

Raw text -> Cleaning -> TF-IDF numbers -> Logistic Regression -> Prediction
This is cleaner than manually calling every step separately.

7. Train/Test Split

The dataset is split into training and testing data:

train_test_split(
    X,
    y,
    test_size=0.25,
    random_state=42,
    stratify=y,
)
Meaning:

75% data is used for training
25% data is used for testing
stratify=y makes sure each class is balanced in both train and test data.

Why split data: we need to test the model on examples it has not already seen.

8. Accuracy

Accuracy tells us how many test examples the model got correct.

Example output:

Accuracy: 0.75
That means the model correctly classified 75% of the test examples.

Important presentation point: the dataset is small, so accuracy is not expected to be perfect. Adding more examples will improve the model.

9. Confusion Matrix

The confusion matrix shows where the model was right and where it got confused.

Example:

Labels: ['reinforcement', 'supervised', 'unsupervised']

[[4 0 0]
 [0 3 1]
 [0 2 2]]
How to explain it:

Rows are actual labels.
Columns are predicted labels.
Diagonal values are correct predictions.
Off-diagonal values are mistakes.
So if supervised gets predicted as unsupervised, it appears outside the diagonal.

10. Rule-Based Layer

On top of the ML model, I added simple keyword rules:

KEYWORD_RULES = {
    "supervised": ["predict", "classify"],
    "unsupervised": ["cluster", "group"],
    "reinforcement": ["reward", "agent"],
}
Why use rules?

Because some words are very strong hints.

Examples:

predict customer churn
The word predict strongly suggests supervised learning.

cluster customers
The word cluster strongly suggests unsupervised learning.

train an agent using rewards
The words agent and reward strongly suggest reinforcement learning.

11. Combining Rule + Model

The model first predicts using Logistic Regression.

Then the rule layer checks for keywords.

The logic is:

If a keyword is found, the rule result is used.
If the model agrees with the rule, confidence is boosted.
If no keyword is found, the model prediction is used.
Example:

Predict customer churn using past data
The model predicts:

supervised
The rule also finds:

predict -> supervised
So final output becomes:

ML Type: Supervised
Confidence: 90%
Reason: Keyword "predict" detected, and the model agreed.
Good presentation line: “The rule layer makes the system more explainable, while the ML model handles cases without obvious keywords.”

12. Confidence Score

The model uses:

predict_proba()
This returns probabilities for each class.

Example:

supervised: 0.72
unsupervised: 0.18
reinforcement: 0.10
The highest probability becomes the model prediction.

When a keyword rule is found, confidence is boosted to at least 85%. If the model and rule agree, confidence becomes at least 90%.

Why: keyword matches are strong signals in this small beginner project.

